    "reasoning": "The goal is to implement an 8-bit priority encoder that finds the index of the least significant bit (LSB) that is set to 1. \n1. The input is an 8-bit vector `in`. \n2. The output is a 3-bit vector `pos`. \n3. Requirement: If multiple bits are 1, return the smallest index. If no bits are 1, return 0.\n4. Implementation Strategy: Use a combinational `always @(*)` block. Iterate through the bits of the input from index 0 to 7. The first time a bit is found to be 1, assign its index to the output and stop searching (using `break`). \n5. Edge Case: If no bit is 1, the output should be 0. To handle this correctly, we initialize `pos` to 0 at the beginning of the combinational block.\n6. Syntax Advice: \n   - Ensure all ports and signals use `logic` as requested.\n   - When using a `for` loop inside an `always @(*)` block, ensure the loop variable is declared locally (e.g., `int i`).\n   - Avoid using `unique` or `inside` as per constraints.\n   - To prevent latch inference, ensure all possible execution paths assign a value to `pos` (initializing `pos = 3'd0` at the start of the block achieves this).",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic [7:0] in,\n    output logic [2:0] pos\n);\n\n    // Combinational logic for priority encoder\n    always @(*) begin\n        // Default value: if no bit is found, output is 0\n        pos = 3'd0;\n        \n        // Iterate from LSB to MSB to find the first '1'\n        for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) begin\n            if (in[i]) begin\n                pos = i[2:0];\n                break; // Found the least significant bit, stop searching\n            end\n        end\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
